    <OBJECT><Parameters><Configure><Task Classes><Timing>:
    Duration: The cycle time of the selected task class can be set in 10 msec
              steps between 10 msec (minimum value) and 5 sec (maximum value).
              All tasks of the task class are processed exactly once within
              this time.
    Tolerance:You can define an allowed cycle time violation for the selected
              standard task class with this entry. In this way, an pre-defined
              cycle time violation is allowed.
    Idle Time:Tasks which have a lower priority than standard high-speed 
              interrupt and exception tasks are processed in the application
              idle time. Communication via serial interface count as idle time
              applications, as well as non-cyclic application tasks, non-cyclic
              operating system routines (e.g. task download/replace) and 
              diverse tools (e.g. debugger). This means that serial
              communication is not possible while cyclic tasks are running!
              For this reason, reaction time problems can occur during serial
              communication in systems with high capacity utilization!


    @155[ Continue ]                        @052[ MM Object ]                     @001[ Overview ]
.155
    PG2000  MAIN MENU FUNCTIONS

              To reduce the distance between the idle time blocks and therefore
              to shorten the reaction time of the serial communication, you can
              configure a so-called task class idle time in 0.5 msec steps for
              the selected standard task class in the entry field "Idle Time".
              By doing this, the set task class idle time for idle time 
              applications is made available to the appropriate task class
              in every task class cycle, after all tasks have been processed.
              If the end of a system cycle is reached within this time span
              (system cycle time = 10 milliseconds), the task class idle time
              is ended. This means that the task class idle time can only only
              be less than 10 msec. In the worst case, the tasks are only 
              processed shortly before the end of the system cycle, and there
              is not much task class idle time left. If normal cycle times are
              used, the standard task class (cycle time = 10 msec) is therefore
              the main application area for the task class idle time.




