    <OBJECT><Parameters><Configure><HS Task Classes><Type>:
    HW Timer:   High-speed task classes are normally called using hardware
                timers (interrupts). We will call these HS task classes 
                Timer HS task classes (abbr.: Timer HSTC).
    RIO/PP FBK: A seperate RIO HS task class (abbr.: RIO HSTC) can also be
                configured for remote I/O systems, as well as Timer HSTCs. The
                RIO HSTC is triggered by an interrupt which is generated by the
                remote master at the end of every RIO cycle. HS task class 2
                (HSTC 2) must always be used for the RIO HSTC!
                A seperate MP HS task class (abbr.: MP HSTC) can also be
                configured for multiprocessors, as well as a Timer HSTC.
                The MP HSTC is not triggered by a hardware timer, but by the
                MP_trigger() function in the application of the main CPU. This
                means that the cycle time of the MP HSTC depends totally on the
                cycle time of that task, in which the MP_trigger() function 
                is called. HS task class 2 (HSTC 2) must always be used for
                the MP HSTC!


    @158[ HS Task Classes ]                 @052[ MM Object ]                     @001[ Overview ]
.161
    PG2000  MAIN MENU FUNCTIONS

    <OBJECT><Parameters><Configure><HS Task Classes><Duration>:
    The cycle time of the current HS task class can be set in 0.1 msec steps
    between 1.0 msec and 65.53 msec.
    The cycle time has different meanings depending on the defined duration
    ("HW Timer" or "RIO/PP FBK") of the current HS task class:
    HW Timer:   All tasks of the Timer HSTC are processed once within this
                this cycle time.
    RIO/PP FBK: The cycle time entered for a RIO HSTC is the minimum cycle
                time. This means that if the RIO cycle lasts 1 msec, and the
                value 3 msec is entered for the cycle time, then the remote 
                master only starts the RIO HSTC every 3 msec, although the
                cycle is already finished after 1 msec. Therefore it is not
                possible for a very fast RIO cycle to overload the system.
                A MP HSTC is controlled by the MP_trigger() function from the
                main CPU. Therefore, the cycle time of the MP HSTC totally 
                depends on the cycle time of that main CPU task in which the
                MP_trigger() function is called. Therefore this entry field 
                has no meaning for the MP HSTC!

    @158[ HS Task Classes ]                 @052[ MM Object ]                     @001[ Overview ]
