    <OBJECT><Parameters><Configure><Remote I/O><Ack. Slave Drop Out>:
    You can set if the slave dropout is to be acknowledged or not in this
    entry field. A remote slave drops out if, for example, the power supply
    for the slave is broken or the bus cable is unplugged.
    Inactive:  The remote system automatically continues the operation for the
               rest of the slaves if a slave drops out.
    Active:    A remote slave drop out must be acknowledged with the RIO_quit()
               function (see RIO library), before the operation of the other
               slaves can continue. No exception is triggered. The remote slave
               remains in ERROR status until it is acknowledged.
    Exception: An exception is triggered if a remote slave drop out occurs
               (exception no. 177). The dropout must be acknowledged using the
               RIO_quit() function of the RIO library, before the operation of
               the other slaves can continue. The remote slave remains in ERROR
               status until it is acknowledged.
    These global settings for individual remote slaves of the remote system can
    be changed using the RIO_mode() function (RIO library).


