    <OBJECT><Parameters><Configure><Remote I/O><Acknowledge Ready>:
    If a remote slave restarts operation after a dropout, (slave becomes READY),
    it is either returned to the RIO cycle automatically ("inactive") or after
    this status has been acknowledged ("active" or "exception"):
    Inactive:  If a slave becomes READY again after dropping out, it
               is automatically returned to the RIO cycle (without 
               acknowledgement!).
    Active:    Before a slave is returned to the RIO cycle with the READY 
               status, the status must be acknowledged with the RIO_quit()
               function (RIO library). This means that this slave remains
               in READY status until the acknowledgement is carried out.
    Exception: If a slave becomes READY again after dropping out, the operating
               system triggers an exception (exception no. 177). Before this
               remote slave is returned to the RIO cycle again, the status must
               be acknowledged with the RIO_quit() function (RIO library).
    These global settings for individual remote slaves of the remote system can
    be changed using the RIO_mode() function (RIO library).


