    <SETTINGS><Compiler>:     * ==> Default Setting

    <I/O Table>:
    While compiling a project, it is possible to optimize the shovel tables
    using these compiler options:

    - Optimized: There is only ONE OPTIMIZED SHOVEL TABLE PER TASK CLASS.
                 (useful for time critical applications, as the I/O variables
                 are only read once per task class).
                 The compiled tasks are NOT EXECUTABLE MODULES (shovel table
                 is extra) and are therefore only allowed to be downloaded
                 to the PCC using the <Object list><RUN> function 
                 (PCC layer pop-up menu)!

    * Default:   Compilation using the set compiler options, in which 
                 every compiled task consists of an executable module 
                 and a PV shovel table.


    @283[ Continue ]                       @055[ MM Settings ]                    @001[ Overview ]
.287
    PG2000  MAIN MENU FUNCTIONS

    <SETTINGS><Compiler>:     * ==> Default Setting

    <Bit handling>:
    The B&R System 2000 CPUs (CP1xx, CP2xx, etc.) handle bit/byte logic by
    hardware means, through the use of an ASIC. This allows optimized bit
    handling, making the commonly used and also rather time consuming process
    of masking in the CPU unnecessary.
    In other processors (C200, etc.), the bit/byte logic must be realized 
    through software. Bit handling in these processors is therefore rather 
    slower when compared with the optimized techniques used in the B&R 2000
    System CPUs.

    * optimized: Optimized bit handling (if Bit/Byte logic is realized through
                 hardware).

    - standard:  Conventional bit handling (where bit/byte logic is realized
                 through software).


    @283[ Continue ]                       @055[ MM Settings ]                    @001[ Overview ]
.288
    PG2000  MAIN MENU FUNCTIONS

    <SETTINGS><Compiler>:     * ==> Default Setting

    <Range Check>:
    - On:    The run time of every array access is monitored for tasks which
             were compiled with the option <Range Check>=on. If the CPU
             recognizes an access to the non-existing element of an array 
             variable, the exception "Range Overflow" is triggered.
    * Off:   Array access are NOT monitored.


    <Check adr(0)>:
    - On:    Every pointer access during run time is monitored for tasks
             which were compiled with the option <Check adr(0)>=on. If the
             CPU recognizes access to a non-existing pointer (address=0),
             the exception "Null Pointer" is triggered.
    * Off:   Pointer access is NOT monitored.



    @283[ Continue ]                       @055[ MM Settings ]                    @001[ Overview ]
