.440
    PL2000 Control Statements:  IF - STATEMENT

    Key Words IF- STATEMENT:

         IF ... THEN          Condition
         ELSE IF ... THEN     Alternative Condition
         ELSE                 Condition(s) not fulfilled
         ENDIF                End Code ABSOLUTELY required


    Depending on the conditions defined by the keywords "if"/"else if" and
    "else", the "if" statement allows branching into different programs
    sections.

    There can be any number of "else if" conditions between the 
    conditions "if" and "else".
    As soon as an "if" or "else if" condition is fulfilled, all other "else if"
    conditions, as well as the "else" condition are ignored and are effectively
    invalid for the current program cycle.    


    @441[ if Statement ]                 @442[ loop Statement ]         @435[ Control Statements ]
.441
    PL2000 Control Statements:  Pseudocode IF - STATEMENT

    IF Condition THEN          ; Key Word - Question - Key Word
       Statement(s)1           ; Program Section for Condition=TRUE
    [ELSE                      ; Key Word for Alternative Program
       Statement(s)3 ]         ; Program section for Condition=FALSE
    ENDIF                      ; Key Word for end of IF block

    Linking Several Request Conditions:
    IF Condition THEN          ; Key Word - Question - Key Word
       Statement(s)1           ; Program Section for Condition1=TRUE
    ELSE IF Condition2 THEN    ; Key Word for  Alternative Program
            Statement(s)2      ;
    [ELSE                      ; Key Word for  Alternative Program            
       Statement(s)3 ]         ; Program Section for Condition=FALSE
    ENDIF                      ; Key Word for end of IF block

    If Condition=FALSE and no statements are executed, the program section
    Statement(s)3 after the keyword ELSE is executed.



    @440[ if Statement ]                 @442[ loop Statement ]         @435[ Control Statements ]
.442
    PL2000 Control Statements:  LOOP - STATEMENT

    Key Words LOOP - STATEMENT:
         LOOP .. TO .. DO     Loop requires: START VALUE ASSIGNMENT with
                              small END VALUE
         ENDLOOP              End code ABSOLUTELY necessary
                              => Loop iterations = (end value - start value + 1)

         LOOP .. DOWNTO .. DO Loop requires: START VALUE ASSIGNMENT with large
                              END VALUE
         ENDLOOP              End code ABSOLUTELY necessary
                              => Loop iterations = (start value - end value + 1)

         LOOP                 END the loop by fulfilling a
         EXITIF Condition     defined EXIT CONDITION
         ENDLOOP              End code ABSOLUTELY necessary
    The "LOOP" statement enables statements to be executed repeatedly, as long
    as the exit condition is fulfilled. Start and end values give a definate
    number of program runs; 'exitif' ends the loop if a specific condition is
    fulfilled. A required loop statement (start and end value) can also be 
    interrupted early with an 'exitif' exit condition.
    @443[ loop Statement ]              @444[ select Statement ]        @435[ Control Statements ]
.443
    PL2000 Control Statements:  Pseudocode LOOP - STATEMENT

    LOOP 
        Statement(s)           ; Statements before the exit condition
    EXITIF logical expression  ; Exit condition of the loop
        [statement(s)]         ; Statements - exit condition not fulfilled
    ENDLOOP

  ATTENTION: The logical expression after "EXITIF" is to be written so that
     it will be logically TRUE during the running of the program. Otherwise it
     causes a cycle time violation (infinite loop).

    Construction of a CONDITIONAL loop statement:

    LOOP  Start assignment TO end value DO   ; (e.g.: loop startval=0 to 200 do)
        Statement(s)           ; Statements of the loop
    [EXITIF logical expression ; Optional early exit condition
        Statement(s)]          ;
    ENDLOOP                    ; Loop ends when the end value 200 is reached
                               ; => Loop iterations = (200 - 0 + 1) = 201

    @442[ loop Statement ]              @444[ select Statement ]        @435[ Control Statements ]
.444
    PL2000 Control Statements:  SELECT - STATEMENT

    Key Words SELECT - STATEMENT:

         SELECT               Start of the Select program section
            STATE ...         Mark a STATE BLOCK
            WHEN ... DO       Transition condition for the NEXT state block
                NEXT ...      Definition of the NEXT state block
         ENDSELECT            End code ABSOLUTELY necessary

    Using the "SELECT" statement, you can switch between various program
    sections (state blocks) depending on different conditions (defined by
    transition conditions).

    Only one state block is ever processed per program cycle.

    By default, the first defined condition block will be executed until the
    program switches states when a transition condition is fulfilled.



    @445[ select Statement ]             @447[ case Statement ]         @435[ Control Statements ]
.445
    PL2000 Control Statements:  SELECT - STATEMENT

    State Blocks and Transition Conditions:

         STATE manu           Mark the STATE BLOCK 'manu'
            Statements_manu   Program section of the state block 'manu'
         WHEN auto_fl=1 DO    Transition condition for the sate block "auto"
            NEXT auto         Branch to the state block "auto"
         STATE auto           Mark of STATE BLOCK "auto"
            :
    Each status block begins with "state". The transition condition starts
    with "WHEN" and must branch to a state block defined with "state", using
    the keyword "NEXT".

    Switching to another state block only occurs after the transition condition
    has been fulfilled. If no transition condition in a state block is 
    fulfilled, the same state block is executed next cycle.

    You can NOT jump to a state block with "goto" !


    @446[ select Statement ]             @447[ case Statement ]         @435[ Control Statements ]
.446
    PL2000 Control Statements:  Pseudocode SELECT - STATEMENT

  SELECT                         ; Key word to start select statement
      STATE Statename(1)         ; Mark 1 st state block
            Statement(s)1        ; Program section of the 1 st state block

      WHEN  Condition(1_1) DO    ; 1 st transition condition
            [statement(s)11]     ; Opt. program section for Condition(1_1)=TRUE
            NEXT Statename(x)    ; Target state block for Condition(1_1)=TRUE
  [   WHEN  Condition(1_2) DO    ; Optional 2 nd transition condition
            [statement(s)12]     ; Opt. program section for Condition(1_2)=TRUE
            NEXT Statename(y)    ; Target state block for Condition(1_2)=TRUE
          . . .                  ; Any number of transition conditions
          . . .                  ; with optional program sections
          . . .               ]  ; and branches to other target state blocks

      STATE Statename(2)         ; Mark the 2 nd state block
        . . .                    ; Any number of state blocks

  ENDSELECT                      ; Key word to end the select statement

    @444[ select Statement ]             @447[ case Statement ]         @435[ Control Statements ]
.447
    PL2000 Control Statements:  CASE - STATEMENT

    Key Words CASE - STATEMENT:

         CASE ... OF             Evaluation of the defined expression which is
                                 implicitly converted to the data type WORD.
         ACTION value:           SELECTION via unsigned constants
         ELSEACTION:             Definition of a DEFAULT ACTION; this is
                                 executed if no "ACTION value" applies to the
                                 "case expression"
         ENDACTION               REQUIRED end code of an action block
         ENDCASE                 REQUIRED end code of a case block


    Using the "case" statement, you can branch to various actions by means of
    different values or ranges of the case expression.

    The definition of an action within a value range is carried out via 2 dots
    (action startval..endval: ; e.g.: action 10..15: ).


    @448[ case Statement ]                @440[ if Statement ]          @435[ Control Statements ]
.448
    PL2000 Control Statements:  Example CASE - STATEMENT

  CASE word1 OF       ; A jump is made to an action according to word1
    ACTION 22:        ;
    ACTION 25..33:    ;
       Statement(s)   ; These statements are carried out if word1 = 22
                      ; or is between 25 and 33.
    ENDACTION         ; End of this action. There must be another action or
                      ; endcase following this.
    ACTION %%111..$f:  ; Range from 7 to 15; does not do anything (empty action)
    ENDACTION         ; Empty action is terminated
    ELSEACTION:       ; This action is executed if no other action
       Statement(s)   ; number matches.
    ENDACTION         ; The else action must also be terminated with
                        'endaction'
    ENDCASE           ; End of the Case construct

  ATTENTION: Max. 512 action numbers are allowed to be used, including all
  numbers of the range (limit of jump table). 19 were used in the above case.


    @447[ case Statement ]                @440[ if Statement ]          @435[ Control Statements ]
.449
    PL2000 Control Statements:  GOTO - STATEMENT

    Key Words GOTO - STATEMENT:

         GOTO ...             Jump to a JUMP LABEL

         ...:                 Definition of a JUMP LABEL with a colon ":"


     The 'goto' statement causes the redirection of the program flow with an
     unconditional branch to the defined JUMP LABEL.
     You should think carefully before using "goto" statements because they
     limit the optimization possibilities of the PL 2000 compiler.

     There must always be a ':' at the end of the JUMP LABEL. The rules for
     allowable characters are the same as for PV names.

     Jumping into a block or between blocks of control statements ("if",
     "loop", "select", ...) must ALWAYS be avoided.


    @450[ goto Statement ]               @451[ adr Statement  ]                 @436[ Statements ]
.450
    PL2000 Control Statements:  Pseudocode GOTO - STATEMENT

       Statement(s)1
    GOTO Jump Label               ; Branch to jump label
       Statement(s)2              ; The statement(s)2 are NEVER executed in this
                                  ; case, as the GOTO branch ALWAYS continues 
                                  ; from the jump label (statement(s)3).

    Jump Label:                   ; Definition of the jump label
       Statement(s)3 


     After statement(s)1 has been processed, the "goto" statement redirects
     the program flow and continues at statement(s)3.







    @449[ goto Statement ]               @451[ adr Statement  ]                 @436[ Statements ]
.451
    PL2000 Statements:  ACCESS/ADR - STATEMENT

    Key Words ACCESS/ADR - STATEMENT:

         ACCESS               Assigning the address of a DYNAMIC VARIABLE
         ADR()                Determining the address of a STATIC VARIABLE

    The "access" statement enables the address determined with 'adr()'
    to be assigned to a DYNAMIC VARIABLE. 

    - An ADDRESS ASSINGMENT with "access" should only occur once in a program.
      To do this clearly, you could assign them in an INIT sub-program.
    - The ADVANTAGE of using dynamic variables is that data type access to
      the dynamic variable is INDEPENDENT, compared to the static variable.
    - However, using dynamic variables requires "clean" programming, as the
      SAME STATIC variables can be used via their addresses by different
      DYNAMIC VARIABLES. Make sure that the AREA SIZES are not EXCEEDED !!




    @452[ adr Statement ]               @454[ sizeof Statement ]                @436[ Statements ]
.452
    PL2000 Statements:  ACCESS/ADR - STATEMENT

    RELATIONSHIP STATIC - DYNAMIC Variables:
    - No reserved memory area is assigned to DYNAMIC variables. This dynamic
      variable can only be used after the address has sucessfully been assigned
      with 'adr()'.
    - The variable whose address is assigned with 'adr()', is not allowed
      to have a dynamic scope. It can have any data type (BYTE, LONG, 
      Structure etc.).
    - A dynamic PV defined with 'adr()'can be assigned to another dynamic PV
      using 'access', but it always points to the static PV.
    - There is NO CONTROL for the length of the dynamic and the actual length
      of the static variable! It is therefore easy to EXCEED the RANGE !!
    DETERMINING THE ADDRESS OF A static variable:  ADR()
    - Not only the start address of static PVs can be given. There are
      many possibilities available:
      - Normal Case - Address of a PV:  ADR(statPV)
      - Address of a PV + Offset:       ADR(statPV + 100)
                                        ADR(statPV + 2 + sizeof(statPV_2))
      - Address of an Element:          ADR(array[5]) or ADR(struct.item_1)

    @453[ adr Statement  ]              @454[ sizeof Statement ]                @436[ Statements ]
.453
    PL2000 Statements:  Pseudocode ACCESS/ADR - STATEMENT

    dynPV ACCESS ADR(statPV)      ; Assign the address of statPV to dynPV
    dynPV = dynPV + 1             ; With this instruction, the static variable
                                  ; statPV is incremented by 1

    dyn_array ACCESS ADR(statPV)  ; Assign the address of statPV to dyn_array
    dyn_array[2] = $0F0F          ; The 3rd ARRAY element from statPV is written
                                  ; $0F0F (the element size is determined by
                                  ; the VD of dyn_array)

    dyn_struct ACCESS ADR(statPV) ; Assign the address of statPV to dynPV
    dyn_struct.item_1 = 146       ; The static variable statPV is written
    dyn_struct.item_2 = 234       ; according to the strucure offset

    - From the above examples, you can clearly see that MULTIPLE USE
      of a static variable is possible !
    - The variable on the left of ACCESS is AUTOMATICALLY set to DYNAMIC 
      scope in the VARIABLE DECLARATION.


    @451[ adr Statement  ]              @454[ sizeof Statement ]                @436[ Statements ]
.454
    PL2000 Statements:  SIZEOF - STATEMENT

    Key Words SIZEOF - STATEMENT:

         SIZEOF()             Determines the PV length (memory req. BIT/BYTE)

    The "sizeof()" statement enables the length (memory requirement) of any PV
    in a PCC program to be determined.

    - If the PV length of an analog data type (BYTE, LONG, Structure etc.) is
      requested, the function returns the size of the PV in BYTES. The size
      for a function call SIZEOF (PV with BIT data type) is received in BITS.
    - Converting bit to byte occurs automatically (like for "Constants")








    @455[ sizeof Statement ]             @449[ goto Statement ]                 @436[ Statements ]
.455
    PL2000 Statements:  Examples SIZEOF - STATEMENT

    PV Declaration:     PV_by         (data type: BYTE)
                        PV_lo         (           LONG)
                        PV_st         (           Structure, 100 byte length)
                        bit_arr[16]   (           BIT)

    Example with the named PV declarations:             ³Result:
