.575
    SOURCE LEVEL DEBUGGER - USAGE

    Functions for Controlling the DEBUG TASK:

    <Start> :  The program is started and runs until the next breakpoint, or
               until the Stop key is pressed.

    <Stop>  :  A running program is immediately stopped.

    <Step>  :  One line of the program is executed. Afterwards,
               the variables redisplayed.

    <Cycle> :  The program is run through ONCE UNTIL the END.


    - The character '>' on the left side of the debugger window indicates the
      line that will be executed next (code pointer).

    - On the bottom of the window frame is an indicator of the program state.
      This is either RUN or STOP.

    @570[ Foot Line Menu ]              @565[ Using the Editor ]                 @002[ DEBUGGING ]
.576
    SOURCE LEVEL DEBUGGER - USAGE

    Using BREAKPOINTS:

    <Breakpoint>   :  SET or DELETE a BREAKPOINT at that point in the program,
                      where the cursor is currently at.

    <Delete>:         DELETES ALL Breakpoints.


    - BREAKPOINTS are marked with the '=' character on the left side of the
      debugger window.
    - If the task was stopped by a BREAKPOINT, the CURRENT CODE POINTER
      LINE is indicated with '>>'.







